The core distinction that matters in production
CPU and memory are fundamentally different types of resources, and Kubernetes treats them completely differently at the kernel level.
CPU is time-based. The Linux CFS (Completely Fair Scheduler) gives your container a quota window — for example, 50ms of CPU time every 100ms. If your app burns through that 50ms in 20ms, it gets forced to sleep for the remaining 80ms and wakes up on the next window. Nothing dies. The app just slows down. This is why CPU problems show up as latency spikes and increased response times, not crashes.
Memory is space-based. The kernel tracks your container's RSS (Resident Set Size) against a hard ceiling set by cgroup's memory.limit_in_bytes. The moment you exceed it by even one byte, the OOM Killer fires a SIGKILL (exit code 137) — no warning, no grace period. The process dies instantly. This is why memory problems show up as OOMKilled in kubectl describe pod.

The throttle trap — the most underdiagnosed problem
The most common misunderstanding in production: a pod can be heavily throttled even when CPU usage looks "normal." If your limit is set too tight relative to your request, every request spike causes the kernel to throttle your process, but kubectl top pods might show 60% CPU and look fine. You must monitor container_cpu_cfs_throttled_seconds_total in Prometheus to see the real picture.

For your Java/Spring Boot apps specifically
JVM is memory-hungry at startup (class loading, JIT compilation). Always set your memory limit at least 1.3–1.5× your -Xmx value, because JVM off-heap (metaspace, native memory, GC overhead) sits outside the heap but inside the cgroup limit. A common production bug: -Xmx512m with a 512Mi Kubernetes limit → OOMKilled every time.
