Here are a few things worth highlighting that go beyond what's in the widget:
Why CPU showed exactly ~500m, not 450m or 600m
The CFS scheduler enforces the quota so precisely that your usage consistently reported 499–503m. That tiny fluctuation is just the metrics-server sampling window not perfectly aligning with the CFS period. You're seeing the ceiling enforced in real time — the kernel literally stops the process when it hits the quota, which is why you never see sustained 600m or 700m readings.
Why memory jumped in large discrete steps (35 → 208 → 345 → 511)
That's the stress tool's allocation strategy. It allocates memory in large chunks (typically 256MB blocks), not gradually. The kernel maps those pages lazily — they only show in RSS when actually touched (written to). So each jump in your kubectl top output corresponds to a new chunk being written. This is also why memory appears to "teleport" rather than creep up linearly.
The most important thing your restartCount=0 tells you
In a real incident, the first question you ask is: "did the pod restart?" If restartCount > 0, it's almost certainly a memory problem — OOMKill. If restartCount stays at 0 but users complain of slowness, it's a CPU throttle problem. Your entire lab session had restartCount=0 with CPU maxed — perfect demonstration of that diagnostic rule.
