Great question — this is one of the most important concepts to get crystal clear. Let me give you a precise, real-world explanation.



Click through the four node scenarios in the widget — especially "Overcommitted" and "No limits set" to see how dangerous misconfiguration looks.

The single most important mental model to lock in is this: request and limit are answered by two completely different systems at two completely different times.

Request is answered by kube-scheduler — a Kubernetes component — at pod placement time. Once the pod lands on a node, the scheduler is done. It never looks at the pod again.

Limit is answered by the Linux kernel — via cgroups — every millisecond the container runs. Kubernetes just translates your YAML number into a kernel cgroup setting when the pod starts. After that, Kubernetes steps back and the kernel takes over.

This is why in your lab the pod could run at 500m CPU (the limit) for 15 minutes even though the request was only 100m. The scheduler used 100m when booking the node. The kernel enforced 500m as the ceiling while the pod was alive. Two separate concerns, two separate actors.

The other thing worth burning into memory: never set limits lower than requests. Kubernetes will accept it but the pod will be throttled or OOMKilled immediately on startup, before it even serves its first request. Limits must always be ≥ requests.


